Ah, I see it now. It's a bit counter-intuitive for a loop or a stream to have an effect when the iterated item is empty.
It could be worthwhile IMO then, for explicitness/clarity, to special case this situation. IE:
if(targetGroups.isEmpty()) {
  targetGroiups.add(new TargetGroup(unitType, targets);
  return;
}


Though, I think it's now more clear to me how we could avoid the mutable 'in/out' parameter, IMHO it would be even better if we returned a value (and also the name of this method becomes a bit easier to refine), eg:

 private static Optional<TargetGroup>  findTargetInTargetGroups( final UnitType unitType, final Set<UnitType> targets, final List<TargetGroup> targetGroups) {
     return targetGroups.stream()
              .filter(targetGroup -> targetGroup.getTargetUnitTypes().equals(targets))
              .findAny()
}

Then the for loop where this is used becomes a bit more clear and the overall control-flow IMO I think is more evident:
    for (final UnitType unitType : unitTypes) {
      final Set<UnitType> targets = findTargets(unitType, unitTypes, enemyUnitTypes);
     targetGroups.add(
           findTargetInTargetGroups(unitType, targets, targetGroups).orElseGet(() -> new TargetGroup(unitType, targets)));
    }

WDYT?

I'm fairly certain that isn't equivalent as it would add the same TargetGroup to the list multiple times. Now you could probably change to an ordered set instead of a list and I think that would then work.
So I generally agree with trying to avoid mutable parameters but this alternative seems harder to understand as you really shouldn't be adding to targetGroups if you find identical targets and instead add to an existing TargetGroup.
So probably if you want mutable parameters then you could do something like:
Optional<TargetGroup> targetGroup = findTargetInTargetGroups(unitType, targets, targetGroups);
if (targetGroup.isPresent()) {
// add unit type to existing target group
} else {
// create and add new target group to list
}

Thoughts? I'm fairly neutral on that vs the existing method as it avoids the mutable parameter but ends up being a lot more verbose.

